SOFTWARE USED: Ubuntu Linux (20.04 / 22.04 or above), Terminal, Internet connection. 
THEORY: Networking commands in Linux help administrators and users to: 
● Configure network interfaces 
● Diagnose connectivity issues 
● Analyze routing and DNS 
● Monitor network traffic 
1. ifconfig (interface configuration) command is used to configure the kernel-resident 
network interfaces. This command is used to assign the IP address and netmask to an 
interface or to enable or disable a given interface. 
Syntax:  ifconfig [...OPTIONS] [INTERFACE]
2. IP command is used for network and routing configuration. This replaces the traditional 
ifconfig and route commands. 
Syntax: ip [OPTION] OBJECT {COMMAND | help} 
Common OPTIONS 
Option -s -4 -6 -c 
Description 
Show statistics 
Display IPv4 addresses only 
Display IPv6 addresses only 
Colored output
3. ping (Packet internet gopher) : Test connectivity between hosts. ping sends an ICMP 
ECHO_REQUEST packet to the specified host.  If the host responds, you get an ICMP 
packet back.  Also you can “ping” an IP address to see if a machine is alive. If there is no 
response, you know something is wrong. Shows packet transmission, latency, and packet 
loss. 
Syntax: ping [OPTIONS] destination
4. Traceroute :  Tracert is a command which can show you the path a packet of information 
takes from your computer to one you specify (Trace path taken by packets.).  It will list 
all the routers it passes through until it reaches its destination, or fails to and is discarded.  
In addition to this, it will tell you how long each 'hop' from router to router takes.  
E.g. traceroute google.com 
$ tracert dmce.ac.in 
5. tracepath command in Linux is used to traces path to destination discovering MTU 
along this path.  It uses UDP port or some random port.  It is similar to traceroute, but it 
does not require superuser privileges .  
tracepath [-n] [-b] [-l pktlen] [-m max_hops] [-p port] destination  
e.g  tracepath google.com (Shows hop-wise delay and MTU size) 
$ tracepath dmce.ac.in 
6. Netstat command is used to examine network connections, routing tables, and various 
network settings and statistics.  
7. dig (Domain Information Groper) is a flexible tool for interrogating DNS name servers. It 
performs DNS lookups and displays the answers that are returned from the name servers. 
e.g. dig dmce.ac.in
